A

There

Its
owner

be
a
giant
with
long

arms.
I
fancy
he
brought
it
from
Naples
or
Sicily.
The
shirt

will
fade
and
will
go
the
way
of
all
shirts

he'll
buy
nice

flannel
pajamas—all
Italians
wear
pajamas,
there
are
dozens

of
them
on
the
lines
in
front
of
my
window;
and
he
will

forget
his
sunny
Italy
and
lose
his
sun-browned
cheeks,
and

how
long
will
it

one

clad
New

Doing
the
same
work,
shoulder
to
shoulder

thous

ands

others

uniform.
Some
elevate
them

selves

average,

to

standard

average.
But

a
while

will

all
be
equal,

all

they
will

walk

and

all
for
one
purpose
to

their
daily
bread.

Over
there
across
the
back
yard
in
front
of
my
garret

a
woman
leans
over

washtub.
She
never
looks
up
to

the
forget-me-not
blue
sky;
she
doesn't
see
the
sparrows

fighting
for
crumbs
of
bread
on
the
fence.
Her
husband

leans
somewhere
in
a
shop
over
his
work
and
is
angry

because
tiny
little
rays
of
the
kind
sun

blinded

little
circles

work.
Not
to

pau

It

lack

wretched.

They

—they

not

They

They

heart

chattering

have

no
time.

Time,
time—just
a
little
time
to
live
is
the
real
plea
of

the
poor
man.

And
how
beautiful
is
life —how
wonderful
is
just
real

life,
even
without
the
comforts
and
blessings
of
civilization.

Life
is
love,
but
we
need
time —just
time
to
do
nothing
but

to
live
and
to
love.
